properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Dangerous wind chill values in the -45 to -55 range has spread across northern Manitoba. These extreme wind chill values will moderate for most regions later today. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. For more information on cold and your health, visit Manitoba Health at https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/environmentalhealth/cold.html or call Health Links - Info Santé at 204-788-8200 or toll-free at 1-888-315-9257. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Bad weather expected this evening and overnight tonight. Intense flurries and strong winds are expected this evening or overnight tonight, momentarily reducing visibilities to near zero in snow and blowing snow. Then, a significant drop in temperatures is expected, which could make some roads icy and slippery. The intense cold will settle during the day on Thursday, and wind chill values could reach between minus 36 and minus 40 Friday morning. Driving conditions may be hazardous at times. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. The next Pacific low will reach the Gulf of Alaska this afternoon while an arctic ridge holds over the N.W.T. Between the two features, a strong pressure gradient will develop late today, forcing strong easterly winds through the gaps in the Richardson Mountains. Easterly winds as high as 70 km/h gusting to 90 will develop late this afternoon near Rock River causing limited visibilities in blizzard conditions. Winds will ease and visibilities will improve early Thursday as the low moves eastward and weakens. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
